  "remissionContext": {
    "title": "Micronutrients and remission support",
    "points": [
      "Micronutrients do not replace medical therapy for Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis, but correcting gaps supports energy, bone health, immunity, and healing while you work toward remission.",
      "Inflammation, diarrhea, bowel surgery, and narrow diets make deficiencies common. Labs (iron, B12, vitamin D, zinc, folate, magnesium) guide whether food alone is enough.",
      "During active flares, many patients use gentler textures and lower fiber until symptoms calm, then rebuild variety in remission.",
      "Pair iron-rich plants with vitamin C (for example lentils with bell pepper) to improve non-heme iron absorption. Separate high-calcium foods from iron supplements when your dietitian advises.",
      "Log meals in IBDPal, bring this food list to visits, and ask: \"Which nutrients should I prioritize based on my latest labs?\""
    ]
  },
